ce:section.ce:para:
For the synthesis of carbon dots (CDs), watermelon seeds were first washed with distilled water and then dried in an open atmosphere at room temperature. To carburize them, the seeds were treated at 300 °C for 5 h in air with a heating rate of 10 °C min−1. Afterward, carburized seeds were ground to a fine powder using a high-energy ball mill (VARSAN) following typical parameters described by Youh et al. [69] i.e., ball to powder ratio was 20:1, at 500 RPM for 6 h without any dispersant. Then 0.1 g of the ground powder (Sample 1) was dispersed in 50 ml deionized water and sonicated for 10 min to ensure complete, and thorough mixing. The effect of the mixture concentration (0.05 g, 0.1 g, and 0.15 g), the reaction temperature (130 °C - 200 °C), and the reaction duration (2 h – 12 h) on the CDs’ formation mechanism was studied by changing one parameter at each time (Table 2
                           ). On completion of the reaction, the solution was first filtered and then centrifuged at 10,000 RPM for 30 min. The supernatant solution was separated, 10 times diluted, and further characterizations were performed. Fig. 1
                           a shows the schematic procedure followed for CDs production.
